Lecture 8. Competing risk models.

This file does not need any special libraries other than the ones listed below. Many of the data sets in this program use data from Hosmer, Lemeshow, and May. I made one minor change, however, which was to force all the variable names to lower case.

First, lets look at this model in a binary fashion, with lost = still in power and natural death as censored observations and constitutional exit and non-constitutional exist as events.

leader$event <- 
  (leader$lost=="constitutional exit") +
  (leader$lost=="nonconstitutional exit")

table(leader$lost, leader$event, useNA="ifany")
##                         
##                            0   1
##   still in power         111   0
##   constitutional exit      0 146
##   natural death           27   0
##   nonconstitutional exit   0 154

binary_surv <- Surv(leader$years, leader$event)

draw_km <- function(v) {
  survfit(binary_surv~leader[ , v], data=leader)   %>%
    tidy                                           %>%
    ggplot(aes(time, estimate, color=strata))  +
      ylab(v)                                       +
      expand_limits(y=0:1)                          +
      geom_step()                                  %>%
  return  
}

draw_km("manner")

draw_km("start_c")

draw_km("military")

draw_km("age_c")

draw_km("conflict")

draw_km("loginc_c")

draw_km("growth_c")

draw_km("pop_c")

draw_km("land_c")

draw_km("literacy_c")

draw_km("region")

binary_mv <-

      manner + 
      military +

    data=leader
  )

Compare the Martingale residuals to each independent variable already in the model to look for non-linearities.

leader$r <- residuals(binary_mv)
ggplot(leader, aes(manner, r))   +
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(leader, aes(military, r)) +
  geom_boxplot()                 +
  geom_smooth(se=TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(leader, aes(age, r))      +
  geom_point()                   +
  geom_smooth(se=TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Competing risk models

surv_object <- 
  Surv(
    leader$years, 
    leader$lost,
    type="mstate")

km_overall <- survfit(surv_object~1)
plot(km_overall$time, km_overall$pstate[ , 1], type="s")

plot(km_overall$time, km_overall$pstate[ , 2], type="s")

plot(km_overall$time, km_overall$pstate[ , 3], type="s")

plot(km_overall$time, km_overall$pstate[ , 4], type="s")
